         <abstract>
            <p>We consider Hammerstein equations of the form $$y(t) = f(t) + \int^b_a k(t, s)g(s, y(s))ds, \quad t \in \lbrack a, b \rbrack,$$ and present a new method for solving them numerically. The method is a collocation method applied not to the equation in its original form, but rather to an equivalent equation for $z(t):= g(t, y(t))$. The desired approximation to $y$ is then obtained by use of the (exact) equation $$y(t) = f(t) + \int^b_a k(t, s)z(s)ds, \quad t \in \lbrack a, b \rbrack.$$ Advantages of this method, compared with the direct collocation approximation for $y$, are discussed. The main result in the paper is that, under suitable conditions, the resulting approximation to $y$ converges to the exact solution at a rate at least equal to that of the best approximation to $z$ from the space in which the collocation solution is sought.</p>
          </abstract>
